text: I tried to dance flamenco but I just ended up playing footsie with the rhythm.
She was so striking in her fashion statement that when she walked by, even the mannequins started to blush.
I don't litter because I refuse to be picked up by strangers.
My retirement plan is a real work of art – it's abstract and nobody understands it.
I restored a painting so well, the museum got a new security guard just to watch me leave.
I bought a silk kimono to connect with tradition, but all I connected with was my bank's overdraft fees.
My mirror tried to teach me about empathy, but I just couldn't see myself in its position.
I tried restoring an old house, but the only thing historic about it now is the amount of money I've sunk into it.
Milan's aperitivo culture is so sophisticated, even the cocktails have to dress up.
Surfing near the reef is a real board meeting for thrill-seekers and fish alike.
I started a T-shirt printing business for invisible ink designs; sales are not visible yet.
I tried to write a poem with a rhyme scheme, but I got stuck in a pattern of debt.
I bought a jacket from Marks & Spencer, but it was a Spencer; now I have to return half of it.
I asked for a Spencer at the tailor, and he gave me a confused look and a biography of Spencer Tracy.
They say with age comes wisdom, but at my age, it just comes with a lot of "back in my day" stories.
I told my vegan friend I got a silk shirt; she said it was offensive, so I guess it's my new "silk-screened" tee.
Artificial reefs are like underwater theme parks, except the fish don't have to wait in line for the rides.
I watched the film "Spencer" about Princess Diana, and now I can't stop curtsying to my reflection.
I fell for a phishing scam because the email said I won a Nobel Prize for gullibility.
I entered a bidding war for a haunted mirror; I wanted to see what all the fuss was about, but I just couldn't reflect the price.
I told my mirror I was learning about symmetry in physics, and it said, "I can see you're reflecting on the subject."
I had a dream about infinite potential, but then I woke up and remembered I have a finite amount of coffee.
I watched an R-rated movie about aging gracefully; it was just two hours of someone trying to read small print.
I tried to start a cultural revolution with my music, but everyone just revolved around the exit.
I visited a Gaudí building and now my own house feels like it's not even trying.
I asked for a silk robe for my birthday, but I guess my family heard "milk robe" because now I smell like a latte.
I told my friend the sky's the limit, so he became an astronaut and now he's just endlessly drifting.
AC Milan and Inter Milan had a match to see who's the best, but it ended in a draw; I guess it was a real tie-ranny of choice.
The Bolshevik Revolution promised power to the people, but all my power socket gave me was an electric shock.
I asked a Spaniard how to balance work and naps; he said, "Take a siesta, then fiesta like it's your job!"
I told my friend my life was like a novel's structure, but it turns out it's less of a gripping storyline and more of a terms and conditions page.
I asked my history book about the French Revolution, but it just gave me a bunch of dates – I guess it couldn't find the right words to "guillotine" the subject.
I was excited about the intrigue in my new job, but it turns out the only thing undercover was the office printer.
I bought some ripened fruit, but it's just sitting there in the bowl, judging all the green bananas.
My printer has such a high carbon footprint, it must be trying to stomp out the competition.
"Choose your own adventure" books are great until you realize flipping to page 64 always ends in homework.
My PlayStation's trophy system is so encouraging, it gave me an award for "Most Time Spent Thinking About Playing."
I lowered the dose of my medication and suddenly, I'm not a superhero anymore.
Milan's economic influence is so strong, even the pigeons at Piazza del Duomo have started trading stocks.
Why did the PlayStation apply for a job? It heard companies were looking for people with good "console" skills.
I tried to write a cliffhanger, but I just ended up with a story that fell off halfway through.
The PlayStation Network is like a party where everyone's too busy playing games to socialize – so, the best kind of party.
They say a gentle word can break a bone, but I've been whispering to my soup for hours and it's still not crunchy.
I received a formal invitation that said, "You're cordially invited..." and now I'm stressed about finding a tuxedo for my cordial.
My 3D printer only prints 3D models of smaller 3D printers; it's like a nesting doll, but for tech geeks.
After the economic downturn, my bank account's idea of recovery is finding loose change in the couch cushions.
Lower management wanted to feel higher up, so now they all wear platform shoes to meetings.
I bought reef-safe sunscreen, but now my emails are all filtered for being too eco-friendly.
I got a high-quality car stereo system installed, but I'm still trying to find the volume control for traffic noise.
I promised to cross my heart, but I drew it in pen, and now I can't get my shirt clean.
I tried to get to the heart of the matter, but I ended up in the spleen of the situation, and now everything's just confusing.
My friend's bakery burned down last night. Now his business is toast.
I asked my mirror about my future, but it just told me I look like someone who believes in superstitions.
I asked Katie why she always wears personalized jewelry, and she said, "It's so I never forget how to spell my name."
My friend's bridal party proposal was so elaborate, I thought I was being drafted for an elite task force.
Katie's so popular, when she created "Katie's Crew," it accidentally became a small island nation.
I lowered the brightness on my phone, and now it's too dim to find its own charger.
The VIP event invitation said "exclusive," but the only thing exclusive about it was the exit door.
Installed a smart garage door opener and now it keeps opening up about its feelings.
Jose can you see? Because after that last round of tequila, I'm pretty sure I can't.
When Jose Mourinho enters a room, even the chairs become defensive.
I enrolled in a class for fundamental skills, but it turned out to be a basic course in how to Google everything.
Jose Feliciano offered to play at my party, but I had to turn him down because nobody could find the light switch.
Parallel lines have so much in common. It’s a shame they’ll never meet.
I prefer downloading my music rather than streaming; I like owning things, like songs and, apparently, buffering frustration.
I'd tell you a chemistry joke but I know I wouldn't get a reaction.
I installed a new security system at home, but the only thing it's caught so far is my interest in how much I spent on it.
My family is like a cell; we divide over everything, especially when it's time to do the dishes.
I went to "Katie's Diner" for some comfort food, but the meatloaf gave me an existential crisis instead.
My social media timeline is like my fridge; I know there's nothing new, but I keep checking every 10 minutes anyway.
I tried to catch some fog this morning, but I mist... it was a gentle attempt.
I was going to study fundamental human rights, but I decided I didn't have the constitution for it.
I played a lullaby at a rock concert and it was a gentle reminder that I should probably update my playlist.
I updated my software and now it's so advanced, it's refusing to work with me until I read the manual.
I gave my girlfriend a heart-shaped map for Valentine's Day; now she knows she's at the heart of my directionless life.
I told my music teacher I understood fundamental frequency, and now she expects me to note everything down.
My CPU is so lazy, it has a "DO NOT DISTURB" sign for every process.
My vacuum cleaner's firmware was updated, and now it's too smart to clean up my messes.
My smart fridge just got a firmware update, now it's giving me the cold shoulder and dieting tips.
They say you can't teach an old dog new tricks, but apparently, you can teach an old printer new firmware.
Cryptography experts make terrible magicians; they reveal their secrets in every hash.
I tried peer-to-peer sharing, but my computer is so antisocial, it won't even accept files from itself.
I told my car it was a Ford Crown Victoria, now it just sits in the driveway expecting a royal procession.
My recycling bin thinks it's a magician; it's always turning bottles into bins.
I bought a crown for my tooth, but now it just sits there on its throne judging the other teeth.
I asked the dentist for a crown, and he said, "Sorry, I only do dental work, not coronations."
I asked a historian for a timeline of events, but he just told me, "It's about time you got a watch."
I asked for a trick or treat, and my neighbor gave me a salad – the ultimate Halloween deception.
I tried to break up with single-use plastics, but they keep saying, "It's not you, it's me."
I was going to tell a joke about an unlicensed firearm, but I realized it's not a laughing matter.
My computer's favorite workout is the algorithm; it keeps saying it's only a few steps to solve any problem.
My parents' divorce was like a magic trick – they split everything, and my college fund disappeared.
I live so close to the time zone line, I celebrate New Year's twice and still get a good night's sleep.
I got into a fight with my Scrabble tiles; you could say words were exchanged.
I love optical illusions, they're the only time I don't mind being visibly confused.
Jump ropes are great for coordination, or in my case, for realizing I can trip on air.
I put "procrastination" on my timeline, but I've scheduled it for sometime between now and the end of the universe.
I tried to strike a deal with my cat to wake me up for work; now I'm late and covered in claw marks.
I tried to master sleight of hand, but now I can't find my fingers.
I told my therapist I hear voices, and she said we should talk about it next time when we're alone.
I bid on a treadmill at a charity auction; I figured it's the only way I'll ever run for a good cause.
I told my friend I was into engineering, and now he thinks I'm responsible for every train delay.
My teddy bear is my most trusted advisor; he always agrees with me when I need a snack at 2 AM.
I sparked a debate on electricity conservation, and now my ideas are shockingly unpopular.
I got a remote-controlled car to fuel my love for speed, but the only thing racing was my dog chasing after it.
They said we had striking similarities, but I'm pretty sure I don't look like a "Buy One, Get One Free" sign.
They said I was a catalyst for change, so I tried to alter my chemistry set, but all I got was a bad reaction.
My library expansion is going great; I've got all the books I'll never read organized by the level of guilt I feel for not reading them.
I tiled my pool myself, which was a great idea until I realized I made a giant Sudoku puzzle.
I acquired a rare historical artifact, and by rare, I mean nobody else wanted a two-thousand-year-old piece of chewing gum.
I bought a thesaurus that was missing pages, which left me unarmed in a war of words.
I asked my therapist how to achieve inner peace, and she said, "Try paying in advance."
I tried to embrace change, but it filed a restraining order for hugging it too tightly.
My company's acquisition strategy is like my approach to dating: I aim high, but usually just merge with the cat on the couch.
I dropped a tile on my foot and now I have a ceramic break instead of a clean one.
I tried to win a silent auction by shouting louder; turns out that's not how you get a library named after you.
My therapist suggested I find an outlet for my anger, so now I have an impressive collection of stolen power strips.
I nodded in agreement so much at the meeting, I left with a job as a bobblehead model.
They say to accept yourself, but when I did, I ended up with two of me and it's getting crowded in here.
I told my friend I was reading a book on anti-gravity weapons; it's impossible to put down.
